Abstract = {{A theoretical framework, a partial correlation-based functional
   connectivity (PC-FC) analysis to functional near-infrared spectroscopy
   (fNIRS) data, is proposed. This is based on generating a common
   background signal from a high passed version of fNIRS data averaged over
   all channels as the regressor in computing the PC between pairs of
   channels. This approach has been employed to real data collected during
   a Stroop task. The results show a strong significance in the global
   efficiency (GE) metric computed by the PC-FC analysis for neutral,
   congruent, and incongruent stimuli (NS, CS, IcS; GE(N) = 0.10 +/- 0.009,
   GE(C) = 0.11 +/- 0.01, GE(IC) = 0.13 +/- 0.015, p = 0.0073). A positive
   correlation (r = 0.729 and p = 0.0259) is observed between the
   interference of reaction times (incongruent-neutral) and interference of
   GE values (GE(IC)-GE(N)) computed from {[}HbO] Signals. (C) 2017 Society
