   AMERICA}},
Year = {{2017}},
Volume = {{114}},
Number = {{43}},
Pages = {{E9145-E9152}},
Month = {{OCT 24}},
Abstract = {{Primates are highly attuned not just to social characteristics of
   individual agents, but also to social interactions between multiple
   agents. Here we report a neural correlate of the representation of
   social interactions in the human brain. Specifically, we observe a
   strong univariate response in the posterior superior temporal sulcus
   (pSTS) to stimuli depicting social interactions between two agents,
   compared with (i) pairs of agents not interacting with each other, (ii)
   physical interactions between inanimate objects, and (iii) individual
   animate agents pursuing goals and interacting with inanimate objects. We
   further show that this region contains information about the nature of
   the social interaction-specifically, whether one agent is helping or
   hindering the other. This sensitivity to social interactions is
   strongest in a specific subregion of the pSTS but extends to a lesser
   extent into nearby regions previously implicated in theory of mind and
   dynamic face perception. This sensitivity to the presence and nature of
   social interactions is not easily explainable in terms of low-level
   visual features, attention, or the animacy, actions, or goals of
   individual agents. This region may underlie our ability to understand
   the structure of our social world and navigate within it.}},
